make rhe modern\nMagic Chef more convenient, make your work easier, and\ngive you more time for pleasure. And. too, the oven of the\nmodern Magic Chef is completely insulated with per\nmanent. thick die-cut blocks which keep the heat inside\nto do its job of cooking, making your kitchen cooler.\nCome into our store today and inspect the many models,\nin many prices, we have on display.\nNOH SPECIAL ON y //Z X\u201d/\n.ALatfic Uief\n$9950 GASRANGE\nFA*Y TERMS IF DESIRED SEE THEM TODAY\nCOAST COUNTIES\nGAS& ELECTRIC COMPANY\n13$ So. Sixth St. El Centro Phone 10\nt.a Kppiiaioes Mav Also Be Purchased at I. V. Hardware Co.\nI tlgar's Hardware Schmitt Electric Co.\nPHONE 300\nmance bond and a $2.500000 bond\nto assure payment of labor and\nmaterials bills.\nGrand Coulee will be 553 feet\nhigh. The power plant, when com\npleted. will contain 18 generators,\neach with a capacity of 105.000\nkilowatts. Water stored behind the\ndam will provide for irrigation of\n1.200.000 acres of land.\nTile foundation for Grand Cou\nlee dam was begun in 1934 and uie\nwork now finished averages a\nheight of 17 i feet above bed rock.\nHeiress Named\nIn Damage Suit\nLOS ANGELES. Jan. 28. <UPI\nGeraldine Spreckels, wealthy so\ncialite and heiress to the Spreckels\nsugar millions, today was named a\ndefendant in a $25,733 damage suit\nfiled by shinjiro Nakamoto. Japa\nnese gardener, who charged Miss\nSpreckels was riding in an auto\nmobile with Capt and Mrs R A\nGardner last July 26 when the car\ncollided with Nakamotos automo\nbile.\nThe Japanese alleged that the car\nin which th\u00b0 plaintiffs were riding\nwas traveling at 60 miles an hour\nin the business district when the\naccident occurred.\nNATIONALISTS\nLAY CLAIM TO\nBIG VICTORIES\nHENDAYE. FRENCH SPANISH\nFRONTIER. Jan. 28. (UP>\u2014Spanish\nNationalists asserted today that they\nhad defeated with heavy loss Loyal\nist attacks north of Teruel.\nSeparate, strong attacks in the\nCeladas sector and the Singra sector\nfarther north were stopped, the\nNationalist Salamanca communique\nasserted, and four Loyalist tanks\nand one airplane were put out of\naction.\nLoyalists, in their Madrid com\nmunique, admitted that there had\nbeen no important changes in the\nCeladas or Singra fighting but they\nheld that Loyalist retained the ini\ntiative They said that fighting\ncontinued.\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\nHELD NOT FAR OFF\nBABSON PARK, Fla., Jan. 28. \u2014It is too early yet to\nsay when the business recession will be over. I am more\ncertain than I was a month ago, however, that a revival\nis not far off There are now straws in the wind which\nshow that business is slowly turning' around. These straws\nwere missing at Christmas time.\nAmong them are good retail trade\nreports, seasonally higher indus\ntrial activity, steadier tones in\ncommodity markets, and better\nbuilding volume. To get a words\neye picture of current trends, let\nme briefly analyze the leading\nbusiness barometers:\nConsumer Industries Sensitive\nConsumer Industries are usually\nthe first to be hit and hence are\nusually the first to recover. There\nfore. conditions in this group at\npresent are of more than ordinary\ninterest. Textile activity is current\nly 40 per cent below last year\u2019s\nlevel and back to the 1932-34 bed\nrock figures. Trading in gray goods,\nhowever, has recently been more\nbrisk and prices have firmed. The\nfortnight, moreover, has seen a\nsturdy step-up\u2014lo per cent\u2014in\n1 mill operations.\nThe shoe industry was among the\nfirst to feel the slackening in ac\ntivity last year. Production last\nmonth was 30 per cent under the\nyear-ago level. Smart shoe-makers.\nI however, have cut prices 10 per\ncent. As a consequence, buying was\nbetter than expected at the recent\nannual Chicago shoe show. Reports\nindicate tljat some factories will be\nrunning near capacity during the\nnext 60 to 90 days.\nOne would think that food sales\nwould jog along at a stable level,\nbut volume is influenced by prices\nand general conditions. Latest re\nports show food sales considerably\nunder the 1937 figures. Here again\nthere has been a noticeable pick-up\nduring the past week or two with\nthe easing off in retail prices as\nthe leading stimulating factor.\nPaper consumption has taken a\n\u201clicking\" along with all other bus\ninesses. Because paper is used in\nso many different lines, it is an\nexcellent barometer of general bus\niness. It is interesting, therefore,\nthat paper company executives re\nport orders nudging seasonally a\nhead in the past ten days with\nmany mills running better than\nthey have for several months.\nSome Heavy Industries Hard Hit\nHeavy Industries maintained\ntheir volume long after the more\nsensitive consumer industries be\ngan to curtail. Hence, some were\nhit later but harder than the light\ner manufacturing group. Biggest\nsuffered among the durable goods\nindustries has been steel. Opera\ntions catapulted downward from\n85 per cent of capacity last August\nto 20 per cent a month ago. Since\nChristmas there has been some\nrecovery and the operating rate\nthis week is around 30 per cent\ncompared with 80 per cent a year\nago.\nMotor assemblies in 1937 were the\nsecond largest in the history of\nthe industry. Car sales continued\nat an excellent level\u2019 until Novem\nber when they folded up like an\naccordion. Factory output has drop\nped from 120.000 cars per week\nlast Spring to 65,000 at present.\nThe current level, on the other\nhand, compares with only 50,000\nassemblies in the first week of this\nI month!\nBuilding volume has held up re\nmarkably well. Private home con\nstruction has fallen sharply since\nlast June and is only 65 per cent\nof the 1937 level But non-residen\ntial and public operations have\nstepped into the breach so mat\ntotal construction in December was\nabove a year ago. Furthermore,\nthe first half of January was bet\nter than the initial fortnight of\nDecember As a consequence, al\nlied industries, such as lumber,\nhave begun to pull up from their\nrecent depth of as low as 50 per\ncent under their 1937 peaK.\nMachine-tool orders are a good\nbarometer of activity in all the\ncapital goods industries. They are\nrunning 45 per cent below a year\ni ago. The December total of do\nmestic orders was off 10 per cent\nfrom November, but latest figures\ni indicate a less-than-seasonal de\ni cline. Meanwhile, foreign orders lor\nour machine tools particularly\nfrom Russia\u2014are coining in brisk-\nI *y-\nGeneral Indicators Look i\u2019p\nMiscellaneous Indicators also give\nI an excellent clue to business con\nditions. Heading the list is power\nconsumption. It is a valuable in\nl dicator because electricity is used\nuniversally in factory and home.\nIts trend has been vertically down\nward since September. Several\nmonths ago output crossed below\nthe \u201cyear ago\" level for the first\ntime since April, 1935. Current fig\nures, however, are reflecting the\nseasonal step-up in industry all\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS. EL CENTRO, CAT.IF.\nPanda Hunter Adds to Laurels\nWhen William H. Harkness died in China seeking to capture alive a\ngiant panda\u2014something no man had ever accomplished before \u2014his widow\ntook up the quest. She was successful and over a year ago brought\nback to America a 2-month-old specimen of the rare animal. Not\nsatisfied, she went back to the wild country on the Tibetan-Szechuan\nborder to seek a mate for the first panda. Now she's on her way back\nwith another, pictured above at Hankow, China.\nBy ROGER BABSON\nover the nation.\nFreight carloadings reliably mir\nrored the down-hill rush of busi\nness shipments this Fall. Loadings\nfor the last week in December were\nat the lowest level for any similar\nweek in four years. Although traf\nfic is still 20 per cent below the\n1937 figures, there has been a\nsharp rebound in loadings in the\nlast fortnight.\nBanking figures are beginning to\nbe optimistic. Commercial loans\ncontinue to slide off gradually\nThey are down six per cent since\ntheir peak in October, showing\nthat inventories are being worked\noff. Bank debits are down 15 per\ncent. On the other hand, deposits\nhave halted their down-trend which\nset in almost a year ago and are\n$100,000,000 above their December\nlows.\nRetail trade is the most optimis\ntic of all the barometers. Merchants\nhave put on attractive \u201csales\u2019 to\nkeep goods moving. As a result, re\ntail trade had held up splendidly.\nChristmas volume was off only two\nper cent from 1936, while January\nclearances have been within 5 to\n10 per cent of a year ago. Good\nretail trade is helping to hold and\nto boost volume in all lines.\nSentiment Baran.rler Weakest\nNow. what does the performance\nof these barometers mean? While\nthey do not definitely show that\nwe have rounded the bottom they\ndo indicate that business is stab\nilizing and that we have probably\nseen the worst. The barometer\nwhich has the lowest reading of\nall right now is \"Business Senti\nment'. Underlying factors have a\nmore important effect in the long\nrun than surface conditions such\nas the present name-calling con\ntest at Washington. But an end to\nthe urrent \u201cEra of Bad Feeling\u201d\nwould do more to heal sentiment\nand to help this mid-winter up\nturn than any other single factor!\nChamber Warns\nAgainst Photo\nRetouch Racket\nEl Centro Chamber of Commerce\nthis week warned housewives to be\non the lookout for itinerant photo\ngraph retouch artists who are\nworking in this city.\nThe retouchers, according to the\nchamber ask for a valued photo\nand offer to retouch it for an\nagreed price.\nA day or so later the men return\nand refuse to give back the photo\nunless the housewife buys an ex\npensive frame for the picture.\nWork of the itinerants is also\nunsatisfactory, the chamber claim\ned.\nEL CENTRANS\nW ILL ATTEND\nROAD MEET\nA delegation of El Centrans will\nattend the annual meeting of the\nImperial Highway Commission Sat\nurday night at 7 o\u2019clock in Elsi\nnore, according to a chamber of\ncommerce bulletin released Friday.\nRobert Hays, president of the\ncommission, will head the list of\nEl Centrans.\nElection of officers and other\nroutine business will be accom\nplished at the meeting.\nParole Revocation\nWill Be Sought in\nBad Check Case\nDistrict Attorney Elmer Heald\nwill request Los Angeles county to\nrevoke Paul Larew\u2019s probation be\ncause he gave $4,800 worth of bad\nchecks to Imperial county ranch\ners to pay for hay. He is on proba\ntion in Los Angeles county after\nconviction on a similar charge\nthere, Heald said. He advised 50\nranchers, holders of the checks, to\ntake this course as it would be\nexpensive to start suit. The Im\nperial Hay Growers association\nhad nothing to do with the deals\nand members are not included in\nthe losses, Roy Wood, manager,\nsaid Friday.\nRAY MATHEWSON\nHERE FOR PARLEYS\nRay Mathewson, district man\nager of the State Employment ser\nvice, was in El Centra Thursday\nfor conferences with officials of the\nservice in Imperial county.\nSNOW ON PALMS\nFT. MYERS. Fla.. Jan. 28 (UP)\u2014\nSnowflakes melted from tropical\nfoliage along Ft. Myers streets to\nday after the first snowstorm in\nthe city\u2019s history.\nThe snowflakes drifted down on\navenues lined with palms, hibiscus\nand oleanders for a brief period.\nYOU haven\u2019t rear ALL the NEWS\nuntil you READ the ADS'.\nused DADPAIUQ\ncar DAIIbAINo j\nAT ROGERS AND TISON S\nHill HWIIWIiI 1 \u25a0\u2014IIOTWr\nI FTTTn WE\u2019RE IJ 11 \u2019TD I\ni F((. hiJihil Not Crazy! i\nI r iz I vou \u2019ll think we are when\nI I yon read these unheard of low v 39\ngjffij W I prices and then come and see A 3N\nI MANY I 'v\u201c 1 B\nfil .MAKES I fZ' voi ro T \\W \\Y 1B\nfl garni MODELS I y >u adf! TO SELL.J B c\nH 'mu Lowest Prices! \\_ A B\nNOW'S THE TIME TO BUY! I\nH Here Are the Cars! Come and Qet f Em! H\nB r/\u2019 ill 1931 AUBURN COUPE \u2014At Only $99 B\nB Khli-110 ImMJ A l _ 1935 CHEVROLET 2-Door Touring Sedan