pect all proj\nects Saturday morning, according\nto Lee Landerman, assistant county\nagent, in a tour that is slated to\nstart at 9 a.m. at the H. C. Worth\nington ranch in Imperial.\nThe group will spend most of\nthe day in touring and inspecting\nthe several projects. Projects to be\nvisited are: Howard and Helen\nWorthington. Norman and Eddie\nCuin, Fritz, Tiny and Joe Landolt,\nBob Landerman, Wally Christian,\nRay Carr. Earl Brinkham, Lyle\nVan Norman. Stanley Hawk, Rob\nert Thompson. Roy and Ben House\nwright, Leonard Chilton. Stanley\nGorman, Joe Lovering, Rachel Wy\natt, and Charlie Cook.\nSTEEL FIRM REPORTS SECOND\nBIGGEST PROFIT IN HISTORY\nNEW YORK. Jan. 28. (UP)\u2014Net\nincome for 1937 of $31,819,596\nsecond largest in the company's\nhistory\u2014was reported today by Eu\ngene G. Grace, president of th\"\nBethlehem Steel corporation.\nThe net profit was equivalent to\n$7.64 a share on the common stock.\nIt has been exceeded only once\u2014\nin 1929. when it was $42,242,980 or\nsll.Ol a share\u2014and was an increase\nof $17,918,590 over 1936.\nReviewing the price-wages situa\ntion as related to his corporation.\nGrace expressed the hop\" that it\nwould not be necessary to consider\nreducing Bethlehem wages, and as\nserted that \"it will be obvious from\na few figures that prices cannot be\nRancher Testifies in\nMail Fraud Actio\nNEW YORK. Jan. 28 (UP)\nAllister Forbes, former Victoria, B.\nC. rancher who lost $30,000 to the\nReno ring of confidence men. testi\nfied today in the third mail fraud\ntrail of William J. Graham and\nJames C- McKay that he was in\ntroduced to McKay by one of the\nmen who swindled him.\nForbes, now of Plymouth, Eng.,\nsaid McKay was represented to\nhim as \"one of the responsible of\nficers\" of the Riverside Bank\nwhere he went to make a draft on\na Victoria Bank at the behest of\nH. H. Stoneman, confidence man.\nStoneman, alias Walter G. Kel\nley, who committed suicide in a\nSan Diego jail recently, took him\nto the bank and explained his de-\nmaterially reduced without adver\nsely affecting wages, which are such\na large part.of costs.\u201d\nCLEVELAND. Jan. 28 (UP)\u2014The\nbandit who entered a chain store\nlast night took time to be fitted\nwith a pair of black oxfords before\nrobbing Joseph Strunk, manager,\nof SB.\nRADIO TECHNICIAN\nFi-ank Naegle\nAll Work Guaranteed\n620 Main El Centro\nPhone 1201\n\nFRIDAY. JANUARY 28, 1938\nsires to McKay, Forbes said.\nThe witness quoted McKay as\nsaying \"We can look after you\",\nand said that after he talked in a\nprivate \"managers\u2019 room\u201d on other\nsubjects, McKay turned him over\nto Joseph M. Feutsch, assistant,\ncashier' who cashed his draft.\nThe government contends Gra\nham and McKay received 15 per\ncent of the confidence ring's pro\nfits, estimated by the prosecution\nto run into the millions, in return\nfor police protection and banking\nfacilities in Reno.\nYOU haven\u2019t read ALL the NEWS\nuntil you READ the ADS!\nTUNE IN\nTODAY\nrefrlshmert\nJW TIME\nSingin'Sam\nF| Deen minute*\nB \u2022Hl\u00dfar Kx?f of S0 \"8 and ha j#\ntnony. Five time*\nweek\u2014Monday*\nthru Fridays.\nKXO 1130 A. M.","height":"29600","width":"23044"}}
